title: Two size Spool Hub with 608 bearing by wigwag

description.text: After printout out my Prusa Handle and Spool Mount http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:28319 I decided to make my own spool hubs. I have two different spools, one from 3dprinterstuff from Amazon and one from Ultimachine. This spool hub fits both.

Step 1: Print two Hubs (you may want to mirror image one if arrows going backwards will drive you crazy)
Step 2: Snap in a 608 Bearing into each.
Step 3: Push fit into spool and add an axis, threaded rod or a number 2 pencil will work. I printed a 7.6mm diameter rod for it since I didn't want to cut rod and couldn't find a number 2 pencil.
Step 4: Place on Spool holder.

description.text: klucz do M10

This is a version of my customizable loupe mount designed to be printed in two parts and glued together. Printed in one piece, the overhanging surface of the clip portion was rough due to the support; I wanted that face printed as a smooth bottom layer. I've extended and thickened the outside shell to give more surface area for gluing, and added tabs and holes to help with alignment. It clips to an iPhone 5/5s with case (Apple leather case) and is designed to work with this $7 60x jeweler's loupe on Amazon. You can adjust the dimensions with DesignSpark Mechanical. Look at the OpenSCAD model in my original design to determine the proper dimensions for your case/thing you want to mount. This one is not customizable using the Customizer, but I have provided the RSDOC file for DesignSpark Mechanical.

Designed to be printed at .20mm layer height and .40mm extrusion width. Other settings may cause issues with the tabs or create gaps in the top of the tube.  
Flip the parts over to print so that the overhanging surfaces are down. The assembled STL is only there to show the complete assembly, although it can be printed with support.  
Parts can be glued together using superglue, 2 part epoxy, or ABS dissolved in acetone if printing in ABS.

description.text:
This thing gives you the ability to create your own parts to fit with copper (plumbing) pipe. :)  
For example, say you want to have a hole to receive a 1/4" copper pipe. Easy, just create a "outside fitting - boolean diff" for "1/4" and however tight a fit you want. Use that to make a hole in your model.  
Or you can do a "outside fitting" and build up your model around the already drilled hole. Either way you like to work.  
You can do the same for inside-fitting connections and even for both inside and outside together.

description.text: Archive model. Not recommended for repetition.

My first 3D printer project Rostock like.
Check it on http://youtu.be/Zh0OgjKmn-M
22 dec 2014 Added effector cap for E3D hotend mount.
Filament feeder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:282969
10/04/2015 added 'effector_j-head_top'
10/10/2015 added new 'diagonal_rod_fix'
10/12/2015 added new direct (on effectors top) extruder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1067150
SolidWorks 2013: https://grabcad.com/library/deltabot-3d-printer-1

Main parts I used:
2pcs IKEA LANTLIV Plant movers
3pcs Nema23 motors (Nema17 is good too)
3pcs Nema23 mounting L-brackets (I have not usual mounts but the bottom parts that I publish is for common mounts from China manufacturers)
6pcs GT2 20teeth pulleys (upper 3pcs could be printed)
5 meters GT2 timing belts
6pcs 800mm long linear shafts 10mm
6pcs LM10 linear ball bushings
12pcs SK10 shaft support blocks
6pcs SA6T/K ball rod ends
6pcs SA6T/K ball rod ends with left-hand thread
6pcs F605ZZ (F605) flange bearings (5x14x5mm)
2 meters 6x8mm aluminium tube (230mm x 6pcs) Is better to check the symmetry of holes in plant movers before assembly shafts mounting parts. Also I used the centering device (look photo) to mount the shaft support blocks. It is the flat aluminium plate with two rigidly fixed 10mm pins. My Marlin-deltabot settings:
DELTA_SEGMENTS_PER_SECOND 200
DELTA_DIAGONAL_ROD 260.0 // mm
DELTA_SMOOTH_ROD_OFFSET 172.86 // mm
DELTA_EFFECTOR_OFFSET 45.79 // mm
DELTA_CARRIAGE_OFFSET 18.82 // mm

comments.text:
About reason I picked Nema23: just I had 3 pcs for free with L-brackets from some old med equipment)). They are smallest in Nema23 series, but you know, they not so bad ), they stay cold all the time and torque are quite good than Nema17.
I added 8mm version of middle part for you, and I'll add the bottom part for Nema17 motors soon... Other parts is the same, just rod mounts would changed on SK8.
With 10mm guides design is less prone to twisting - 8mm will require additional reinforcing structures connecting the upper and lower panels. I don't tested that kind of modification (even haven't printed this parts) and you'll assemble it on your own risk.
About plans to realise design files - tell me part you want and I'll send it to you by email (SolidWorks 2013).
